  "prompt": "How are charter schools different than public schools?",
  "response": "Here are key differences between charter schools and traditional public schools:\n\n1. Funding and Governance\n- Charter schools receive public funding but operate independently from traditional school districts\n- They have more autonomy in curriculum, staffing, and management\n- Typically governed by a separate board or organization\n\n2. Admission\n- Traditional public schools must accept all students in their district\n- Charter schools often use lottery systems if applications exceed available spots\n- May have specific educational focuses or teaching approaches\n\n3. Accountability\n- Charter schools must meet specific performance standards to maintain their charter\n- Can be closed if they consistently underperform\n- Traditional public schools have different accountability measures\n\n4. Curriculum and Teaching\n- Charter schools can design more flexible, innovative curricula\n- May emphasize specific areas like STEM, arts, or college preparation\n- Have more freedom in teaching methods and educational approaches\n\n5. Teacher Requirements\n- Charter schools often have different certification requirements\n- May hire teachers with alternative credentials\n- Traditional public schools typically require state teaching certifications\n\n6. Oversight\n- Charter schools are authorized by state or local educational agencies\n- Subject to periodic review and potential renewal of their charter\n- Traditional public schools have more consistent, standardized oversight\n\nBoth are publicly funded and do not charge tuition, but operate with different structures and philosophies.",
